The electrochemical performances of SC devices were assessed using CV, GCD, long cycle life, and EIS measurements, with SC devices utilizing pH, pH-GO1, pH-G0.05, and pH-R0.05 as active electrodes in symmetrical sandwich-type configurations, including a PVA/H3PO4 gel electrolyte (Fig. 5
                     ). Initially, a typical capacitive behavior was examined via CV and GCD for all samples, exhibiting nearly perfect rectangular CV shapes over a 0–1 V voltage window at a scan rate of 10 mV s–1 and symmetric triangular-shaped GCD curves with negligible IR drop at a specific current of 0.14 A cm–3 (Fig. 5(a, b)). This quasi-ideal capacitive behavior underscores the superior performance of the active electrodes. Additionally, the as-prepared materials showcased excellent rate-retention capabilities, maintaining quasi-rectangular CV shapes under increasing scan rates from 50 to 250 mV s
                     −1 (Fig. S5(a–c)) [48]. At the maximum scan rate of 500 mV s–1, the CV shape preserved its mirror-image symmetry, indicating reversible and rapid charge accumulation at the electrode-electrolyte interface (Fig. S5(d)) [6,49]. Moreover, all GCD plots retained characteristic symmetrical triangular shapes with increasing specific currents from 0.28 to 2.78 A cm–3, highlighting the outstanding rate performances of the active electrodes and their purely capacitive nature (Fig. S6) [2,6].
